ted Kingdom":"Derbyshire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Barley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Barley Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Croxhall, Derbyshire, England":"Croxall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Barley. Those in Lancashire and Yorkshire are named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘wild boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. A place of the same name in Hertfordshire has as its first element an unattested Old English byname <i>Be(o)ra</i> (from <i>bera</i> ‘bear’).","English: metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of barley, from Middle English <i>barli</i>, <i>barlich</i> ‘barley’ (Old English <i>bærlic</i>, originally an adjective derivative of <i>bær</i> ‘barley’, a byform of <i>bere</i>).","Americanized form of South German   Behrle   or of its Swiss German cognates <b>Beerli</b>, <b>Berli</b>, or <b>Berly</b>, and probably also of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Berley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Behrle","meanings":["South German (Württemberg): from a pet form of   Behr   ‘bear’, including from a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with Old High German <i>bero</i> ‘bear’.","Altered form of Norwegian <b>Berle</b>: habitational name from a farmstead in the county of Sogn og Fjordane, so named with Old Norse <i>barth</i> ‘rim, edge’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir George Barley Knight II was born in 1300, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir George Barley I, was 30 and his mother, Lady Ursula Curzon, was 26. He married Isobell Alice Curzon in 1329, in Croxall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1360, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1300–1360":"1300–1360","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1308–Female":"1308–Surnud","1302–1364":"1302–1364","1330–1390":"1330–1390","1334–1400":"1334–1400","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1274–1334":"1274–1334","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1390":"1390","1304":"1304","1302":"1302","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","1306":"1306","Albury, Hertfordshire, England":"Albury, Hertfordshire, England","Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Derbyshire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Derbyshire, Inglis